f Heideggerian ontology articulated in beloved community. Tracking the presence of twentieth-century German philosophy and theology in his thought, the book situates King's ontology conceptually and socially in nonviolent protest. In so doing, The Critique of Nonviolence reads King's "Letter from a Birmingham Jail" (1963) with Walter Benjamin's "Critique of Violence" (1921) to reveal the depth of King's political-theological critique of police violence as the illegitimate appropriation of the racialized state of exception. As Thompson argues, it is in part through its appropriation of German philosophy and theology that King's ontology condemns the perpetual American state of racial exception that permits unlimited police violence against Black lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican American philosophy. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aNonviolencexPhilosophy. 0aOntology. 0aPhilosophy, German. 0aRacexPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aAfrican American philosophy.  aBlack power.  aGerman philosophy.  aNonviolence.  acivil rights.  agnosticism.  aontology.  apolice violence.  apolitical theology.  atheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363208040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632080/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles